NEURAL NETWORKS - COMPUTER VISION
¶

Ricardo López Ruiz
¶

Date: 26/07/2021

Abstract:
¶

Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) are trained to classify plant's species from the images taken of the plants.

Tools used in this project:
¶

'Tensorflow', 'Keras', 'CNN', 'Input/Hidden/Output Layers'

Project - Image Classification using CNNs in Keras¶

Goal:¶

The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo.

Data Description:¶

You are provided with a dataset of images of plant seedlings at various stages of grown. Each image has a filename that is its unique id. The dataset comprises 12 plant species.

Dataset:¶

The data file names are:

  • images.npy
  • Label.csv

The original files are from Kaggle. Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to images.npy file and the labels are also put into the Labels.csv.

Steps and Tasks¶

  • Import the libraries, load dataset, print shape of data, visualize the images in dataset.
  • Data Pre-processing:
    • Normalization.
    • Gaussian Blurring.
    • Visualize data after pre-processing.
  • Make data compatible:
    • Convert labels to one-hot-vectors.
    • Print the label for some element i of y_train[].
    • Split the dataset into training, testing, and validation set.
    • Check the shape of data, reshape data into shapes compatible with Keras models if its not already.
  • Building CNN:
    • Define layers.
    • Set optimizer and loss function. (Use Adam optimizer and categorical crossentropy.)
  • Fit and evaluate model and print confusion matrix.
  • Visualize predictions for some elements i of x_test[].

Building CNN¶

Importing required libraries

In [33]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential          # Sequential groups a linear stack of layers into a tf.keras.Model.
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D              # This layer creates a convolution kernel that is convolved with the layer input to produce a tensor of outputs.
from tensorflow.keras.layers import MaxPooling2D        # Max pooling operation for 2D spatial data.
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Flatten             # Flattens the input. Does not affect the batch size.
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout      # Dropout: Applies Dropout to the input.
                                                        # Dense: Just your regular densely-connected NN layer.

Defining layers

In [34]:
# Initialising the CNN classifier
classifier = Sequential()

# Add a Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
classifier.add(Conv2D(32, (5, 5), input_shape = (128, 128, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

# Add a Max Pooling layer of size 2X2
classifier.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.2
classifier.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Add another Convolution layer with 64 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
classifier.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

# Adding another pooling layer
classifier.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.3
classifier.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Add another Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
classifier.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'valid'))

# Adding another pooling layer
classifier.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.4
classifier.add(Dropout(0.4))

# Flattening the layer before fully connected layers
classifier.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected layer with 512 neurons
classifier.add(Dense(units = 512, activation = 'relu'))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.5
classifier.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Adding a fully connected layer with 128 neurons
classifier.add(Dense(units = 128, activation = 'relu'))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.5
classifier.add(Dropout(0.5))

# The final output layer with 12 neurons to predict the categorical classifcation
classifier.add(Dense(units = 12, activation = 'softmax'))

# Summary of the model
classifier.summary()

Setting optimizer and loss function

In [37]:
#Adding Early stopping callback to the fit function is going to stop the training,
#if the val_loss is not going to change even '0.005' for more than 10 continous epochs
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping
from tensorflow.keras import optimizers 

# initiate Adam optimizer
opt = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999, epsilon=1e-08)

# Compile the model
classifier.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"], optimizer=opt)

# Use earlystopping
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, min_delta=0.005)

#Adding Model Checkpoint callback to the fit function is going to save the weights whenever val_loss achieves a new low value. 
#Hence saving the best weights occurred during training
model_checkpoint =  ModelCheckpoint('cifar_cnn_checkpoint_{epoch:02d}_loss{val_loss:.4f}.h5',
                                                           monitor='val_loss',
                                                           verbose=1,
                                                           save_best_only=True,
                                                           save_weights_only=True,
                                                           mode='auto',
                                                           period=1)
# Summary of the model
classifier.summary()

Fit and Evaluate the Model¶

In [40]:
# Fit the model with validation_split=0.5
history = classifier.fit(X_train,y_train,
                         batch_size=32,
                         epochs=30,
                         validation_data=(X_test, y_test),
                         validation_split=0.5,
                         shuffle=True,
                         verbose=1,
                         callbacks=[early_stopping,model_checkpoint])

# plot training history
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='train')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='validation')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
